<div class="scroll" style="padding-top:8px">
  <div class="abtit">Good feedback makes<br>better towns</div>
  <div class="ablead">
    Running a town is hard work. Keeping corridors clean, maintaining lifts, fighting pests — a hundred small things to juggle at once. And like anything complicated, it's hard to tell what's working and what needs more attention. Most feedback arrives one complaint at a time, from a handful of voices — useful, but never the full picture.
    <br><br>
    RateMyTown makes it easy for residents to share their experience, honestly and openly. Residents get a simple way to be heard without having to fight for it. Town councils get something rarer: a clear, representative read on what residents actually think — where to focus next, proof that improvements are landing, and recognition for good work that would otherwise go unnoticed.
  </div>

  <div class="abh">What we believe</div>
  <div class="abrow">
    <div class="abnum">1</div>
    <div>
      <div class="abrt">Real residents, real experiences</div>
      <div class="abrd">Every rating comes from a Singpass-verified resident of that town. No bots, no spammers, no astroturfing.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="abrow">
    <div class="abnum">2</div>
    <div>
      <div class="abrt">Honest anonymous feedback</div>
      <div class="abrd">Reviews are anonymous so you can share your real experience. We verify you live in the estate, then forget who you are.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="abrow">
    <div class="abnum">3</div>
    <div>
      <div class="abrt">Sunlight, not hostility</div>
      <div class="abrd">We're here to shine a light on problems, not tear anyone down. Clear information shows what residents care about — and helps everyone make better decisions.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="abquote">“The best estates are built when residents and town councils can see the same honest picture — and work from it together.”</div>

  <div class="abh">The thinking behind it</div>
  <div class="abprose">If a shop treats you badly, you stop going — and that freedom to walk away is what quietly keeps most services honest. But you can't walk away from your own estate. You can't switch town councils the way you'd switch supermarkets. When leaving isn't an option, speaking up is the only lever left. And when no one's really listening, the small problems don't get solved — they just pile up, year after year.</div>
  <div class="abprose">The catch: when giving feedback takes real effort — calling a hotline, writing in, chasing for a reply — the only people who do it are the ones upset enough to push through. That's not a flaw in anyone's character; it's simply what effort filters for. But it means what a council hears is mostly anger, from a few voices, about a few issues, while the hundreds who are quietly satisfied — or mildly annoyed, but never enough to write a letter — stay invisible. Anger shouldn't be the price of being heard. Make feedback take two minutes instead of two weeks, and the full picture, good and bad, finally shows up.</div>

  <div class="abh">Better for town councils, too</div>
  <div class="abprose">That fuller picture is exactly what a well-run council needs. When feedback arrives only as complaints, every decision involves guessing whether the loudest voice speaks for the whole estate or only for itself. Representative scores restore proportion: the confidence to put limited time and money where most residents actually need it, and the backing to make a considered call even when a few voices disagree loudly. Nobody should have to run an estate by decibel.</div>
  <div class="abprose">It also means good work finally gets seen. Complaint channels only record what breaks — nobody calls a hotline to say the lifts have been reliable all year. Steady ratings from verified residents show what's going well, whether this year's efforts are landing, and give the people doing the work something a complaints log never will: recognition.</div>
  <div class="abprose">Making this public isn't about naming and shaming. Transparency only changes things when it reaches the people who can act, shows them a clear way to improve, and carries real weight. That's what RateMyTown.sg is built for: not a complaints box, not pressure for its own sake, but honest information placed where it can actually do some good.</div>

